Supporting North 3: Treating critical patients

We are January 26 afternoon officially in Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital, after a day of protection training before admission. It should be said that the condition of the Golden Pool Hospital is quite serious.

This is a special hospital in Wuhan for patients with severe COVID-19 pneumonia, there are more than 400 patients scattered in various wards, about 130-140 severe patients. The hospital is mainly divided into the southern district and the northern district. Our Shanghai medical team is responsible for taking over the wards on the second floor of the northern district and the third floor of the northern district as a whole, adding up to more than 70 patients. The patients on the north second floor are a little better. The North third floor is full of critical patients. The Ward of the North Third District is specially rebuilt by the general ward of the hospital this time, the rescue condition is relatively simple.

I'm in charge of the heavy north third. Twenty-nine critically ill patients, 16 of whom were hooked up to a ventilator, were critically ill, many of whom Oxygenation only 90%-91% . Severe cases, the elderly will be a little more, there are 30-year-old young people. Critically ill patients are characterized by breathing difficulties, pulmonary fibrosis, and sometimes oxygen is not easy to import.

When we went in, the original paramedics were exhausted. Their work rhythm is especially intense, intensity is big, personnel is few, material is short of. Before this ward, there were only 7-8 doctors and 40 nurses working round the clock. The workload was very, very heavy. To take care of so many patients, some of them almost never go home at night, 24 hours in the hospital, has been nearly a month, very tired.

On the other hand, the gold and silver pool is still continuously receiving new patients, two new wards opened two days ago. On my first day, I was coming out of the ward from work when the ambulance brought the patient in. So they're gonNA need all the help they can get. This time, the state supported Hubei Province by adopting the mode of counterpart support. In addition to us, the Army Medical University also supports the hospital, mainly responsible for the North district 4-6 floors.

Shanghai medical team to support the first batch of 136 medical personnel, from the major hospitals in Shanghai. There are more than 30 doctors and 90 nurses in the Department of Critical Care Medicine, infectious diseases and respiratory diseases, as well as other physiological subjects such as digestion and blood. They are mainly divided into more than 70 general and 60 critical care teams.

January 23, small, Ruijin Hospital leadership informed us that the Wuhan side of the emergency, Shanghai to organize medical teams to support. Because at that time said Wuhan needs the serious illness aspect expert, I happened to also do the serious illness medical, immediately reported the name up.

My wife and I both graduated from Second Military Medical University, military background, and although we retired from the army, we still felt a sense of military duty. In 2003, when SARS, I also participated in some prevention and control, but did not go to Beijing Xiaotangshan Hospital such a line. Now the country is in trouble, stand up is the bounden duty, the country needs you, you have to go to the most needed place.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the morning of the New Year's Eve, the hospital called me and said the Registration Health Committee approved, "you hurry to participate in training! " I hurried to the training, training for about two hours, mainly about the protection of some COVID-19 knowledge. After the training, I asked about when I would leave? At that time, I was told that I had not been informed. "I think I will go to a similar new hospital in Xiaotangshan in Wuhan. It may take a few days. " I went back to have dinner on the eve of the Lunar New Year.

On the evening of the New Year's Eve at six o'clock, as soon as the family dinner was served, the phone call came and said, "we are leaving this evening right now! You Hurry to the hospital and go to the airport as soon as you get the supplies from the hospital. " I ate a bowl of home rice in a hurry, and then I was out the door.

My family is still very supportive, but I can't say that I don't have concerns. It's mostly personal protection. Before leaving, my lover repeatedly told me, "must do a good job of protection. ". She helped me prepare some new year's clothes, I put it on that night, as a talisman. And I have a lot of personal stuff, because I know I'm not gonNA be back for a while.

Protection Training: Zaire Ebolavirus

The Shanghai medical team arrived in the early morning on the first day of the Lunar New Year. There will be a day-long training, mainly the experts arranged by the Health Commission to do some self-protection related training, to achieve zero infection of medical staff. One of the highlights of the training is how to wear protective gear. What's the order of dress? What's the loading sequence? It's very elegant.

The silver lake ICU is divided into several sections, from the point of view of protection is the clean area, buffer zone and contaminated areas. The wearing of protective equipment in a clean state is not a big problem, but it is very important to disassemble. When you come out of the intensive-care unit, what's the sequence for removing the virus? This is very important. It's contaminated material, and if it's not in the right order, it could expose you. It's very dangerous, especially when you get to the ward, things change, you panic, you might forget how to do it.

Because the work needs, the work time must put on the goggles, in the cold winter day, the goggles are always separated by a layer of mist. (photo by Takaboshi)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The first day we arrived, we were practicing, over and over again, putting on and unloading. It was much more complicated than on the plane with the Oxygen Mask. It would take 10-20 minutes just to unload and sterilize every step. Like my larger body, clothes do not fit very well, wear and take off are very difficult, do not fit on the risk of exposure, need to pay attention repeatedly.

For medical staff to visit a critical patient in an intensive care unit, secondary care is required, but sometimes very dangerous procedures, such as tracheal intubation, are required in the ICU, and tertiary care is required.

Fortunately, we found that the Golden Pool of health care workers do a very good job of protection, the current health care workers are basically not infected, they pay special attention and efforts in this regard. Of course, it's not that patients with severe illness are highly infectious, as are patients with mild illness, except that patients with severe illness may cough more, spray more than patients with mild illness, slightly higher risk of infection.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the other hand, it is strange that the examiners of the gold and Silver Lake Laboratory never touch patients, just do tests and tests, but the results of four infected. How did they get it? One possibility, experts speculate, is that during high risk operations such as laboratory testing, a patient's blood sample is exposed to the air to form an aerosol that carries the virus to the four examiners. Well, if that's the case, then the virus is very powerful, and if you don't touch the patient, a little bit of blood gets out, and it turns into an aerosol, you can get infected. Therefore, the transmission route can be divided into contact transmission, droplet transmission, air transmission, the main transmission route it may all account.

Finally, we have multiple layers of protection internally, with reference to the army medical university's Zaire Ebolavirus. I also had protection when I worked in the ICU, but mainly to prevent the spread of drug-resistant bacteria, not particularly strict, because it is not contagious. It is usually to wear isolation clothes, masks and hats, masks general surgical masks on it. Now it is necessary to wear protective clothing, protective clothing outside wearing isolation clothing, with goggles, masks and masks, there are two gloves, two hats. Some of the women had their long hair cut off to prevent infection. If we protect ourselves, we'll be able to treat more critical patients.

"here comes the hard way. "

Since we're taking over as a team, we've taken the time to make the transition, and so far, it's going pretty well, and we've left a liaison here at the money pit to coordinate and coordinate.

We thought we had enough for a week, but when we got there, we found out that there were only 500 suits left in the pool, enough to last two days. We may have enough supplies for a week. It's all for emergencies. At present, the material is still a lead a day, a shortage, we have reported the demand up, I believe that the follow-up through coordination can be effectively resolved.

Because the ward of the North Third District is a general ward transformation, so the rescue condition is very limited. In general, the general ward can not do ICU, the formal ICU oxygen source gas source has certain requirements, power system has two sets, because involves a lot of equipment use. For example, oxygen, now there are 16 people in the ICU who plug in the machine, more may not be able to afford, because there will be insufficient oxygen in the ward. Too much equipment, the power goes out.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Our doctors schedule A six-hour shift every day, a 12-hour night shift every five to six days. The six hour work day is very intense, wearing special protective equipment to work in a special environment, very boring, and the patient is seriously ill, but ward conditions are relatively limited, the work will be a little bit harder than expected. Six hours without food, water, stool or urine, 10 to 20 minutes a day. We've got a lot of patients, we've got a lot of work to do, and the paramedics are going in and out of the ICU. Maybe we come out after rounds to write orders, and the patient's condition changes, and you have to go in wearing a new suit, so every day is a lot of material consumption.

We were a little shorthanded when we first came in. The patient to doctor ratio in the General ICU is 1:0.8, infectious disease is best 1:1.2, the nurse should be assigned to 1:3, even 1:3.5,29 patients need at least 87 nurses. When they first moved in, there were only 48 nurses in the north third district, and they had to work eight hours a day, so they were very, very tired. In the intensive care unit should not work too long, the ideal length of day is 4 hours, a long time, a wet mask, it lost its protective effect. Winter cold, this 8 hours can not turn on the heating and air conditioning, cold hands are almost frozen numb, very hard. Heater is also afraid to use more, for fear of ICU trip.

After coordination, the North 2 ward team assigned us 15 nurses, the original 8-hour shift may become 6 hours. A second medical team from Shanghai arrived, along with 50 additional nurses, to relieve the pressure. But because of the shortage of materials, we do not dare to add too many people, otherwise the consumption will be very large, this is also a dilemma.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
I don't know who you are, but I know who you are for

Therefore, the existing medical staff will be a bit more difficult. But we are here to eat bitterness, not to enjoy happiness. We are all prepared for this. Everything is going according to plan, including the rules and regulations for our medical care, the procedures, and the establishment of the Temporary Party branch. The old party members should calm their minds and be ready to fight hard.

On the whole, some of the patients are getting better. My Ward has a 30-year-old young man, has been in the treatment of two weeks, breathing difficulties, breathing very hard, on the suction machine. The first night I took over, he was only about 90% Oxygenation, and I thought, "that's a lot of weight. That could be tricky. " . We had a paramedic on duty that night, and I went the next day, and the Oxygenation was up to 93 percent, and he said he was feeling a little better, and there was a patient in his 40s and 50s who was delirious and sometimes delusional and very unstable. We've given him mental work, medication, and he seems to be stable for now.

We also had our first new patient, who arrived in critical condition, with a minimum of 40% Oxygenation, and after intensive care, we now have 98% Oxygenation, and we are conscious. Anyway, the patients are still coming in, and we never thought we'd be back, and it's time for a pep talk.
